<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-777-060  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 777 060.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  July 9 1990 v219 n2 p26(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Video DS3 fiber gets smart; a chance conversation led to apurposefully crafted partnership between the University of Mainesystem and New England Telephone that has extended opportunitiesfor college education to all state residents.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Paulson, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Maine, wanting to satisfy an 'equal access to quality education'mandate, needed a system adequate for sparsely populated regionswith harsh winter and spring weather.andP;  While Pam MacBrayne,working for the University of Maine, was considering ways to useelectronic communications technology, a chance conversationbetween Augusta campus Pres George Connick and John LaForge, anexecutive with New England Telephone (NET), resulted in staffmeetings at NET that determined that a digital video DS3 fibernetwork was both technically feasible and cost competitive.andP;  Itwas a perfect match: the proposed Distance Education Networkrequired fiber circuits all the way to campuses on the Canadianborder; and NET needed a customer to justify laying hundreds ofmiles of multifiber cables.andP;  The Maine Public Broadcasting Networkwill operate the system, which is a success story that could berepeated in other states.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   New England Telephone and Telegraph Co. (contracts)NYNEX Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    NYN.andO;Topic:     Maine, University ofTelephone systemsFiber opticsColleges and UniversitiesMaineBell Regional Holding CompaniesDistance Education Network (computer network)Interactive SystemsVideo SystemsMaine Public Broadcasting NetworkInformation services.andO;Feature:   illustrationmap.andO;Caption:   Regional map showing university campuses. (map)Person:    Connick, George (management); LaForge, John (management);MacBrayne, Pam (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>